definition.value: gist is a minimalist upper ontology created by Semantic Arts.
A bounded region (or set of regions) on the surface of the Earth.

example.value: The bounded shape that defines the region occupied by Crater Lake; the bounded area known as the contiguous USA.

scopeNote.value: A GeoRegion could be non-contiguous; e.g. the region governed by the USA is the region governed by the lower 48 states plus that of Alaska and Hawaii.  Child classes in lower ontologies can make this distinction.
A GeoRegion has an area, but it is not itself an instance of the Area class.  (Area in gist is a magnitude).

definition.value: An ordered set of GeoPoints that defines a path from starting point to ending point.
An event which occurred in time, with an actual end earlier than the present moment.
A magnitude expressed as a product of primitives.  (E.g., Force = M*A).
An event that has started but has not yet ended.

scopeNote.value: When the event actually ends, it will cease being contemporary.

definition.value: Content expressed as words and numbers (not graphics).
A human being that may or may not still be alive.

example.value: Negative example:fictional characters.

definition.value: Any place an electronic message (email, fax, etc.) can be sent.
A description of things one is prevented from doing.  Most laws are restrictions.
An agreement having a balance, as in a bank account, or credit card account, or Accounts Receivable account.
A reference to a place (real or virtual) that can be located by some routing algorithm, and where messages or things can be sent to or retrieved from. E.g. PO Box or URL to a PDF file.
Content that is used to uniquely identify something or someone.

example.value: SSN for a person; serial number for a product; employee ID.

scopeNote.value: This is used in conjunction with gist:isIdentifiedBy

definition.value: A network is a set of nodes connected by links.

example.value: A physical network could include connected computers or routers, whereas a social network would consist of related Person or Organization instances.

definition.value: The things that a sensor can sense, such as light, heat, current, moisture, etc.
A collection in which the members are sequentially ordered. All members of an OrderedCollection are OrderedMembers.

scopeNote.value: Includes collections in which members occupy the same position in a 'tie,' but not empty collections.

definition.value: The difficulty of reversing a commitment.

example.value: A car rental typically has a lower degree of commitment than an airfare reservation.

definition.value: A flow of electric charge.
A unit of counting, especially ?each?, but also units such as dozens.
A generic organization that can be formal or informal, legal or non-legal. It can have members, or not.

scopeNote.value: There are a plethora of different kinds of organizations that differ along many facets, including members, structure, purpose, legal vs. non-legal, etc.

example.value: Legal entities like companies; non-legal entities like clubs, committees, or departments.

definition.value: Amount of a substance, as counted molecules.
An event with a probability of happening in the future, and usually dependent upon some other event or condition.
A function is what a specific made item is intended to do.  For instance: transmit electricity, provide ballast, control ambient temperature.
Units of three-dimensional space, expressed here as an area times a distance.
Offering something which could be physically warehoused or digitally stored.
Content which has been expressed, either to print, or through speakers, or on a monitor.
A description of something that can be done for a person or organization (which produces some form of an act).
A description of things one is permitted to do. This could be broad, such as free speech, but more often is very specific, such as the right of egress through a particular property.
Non-corporeal material, i.e. 'stuff' which can be divided into parts where each part retains its essence.

example.value: An amount of water, of penicillin, of sand, of gold: an actual piece of gold, not the concept of gold.

scopeNote.value: An instance of this class must be a physical thing, and not just a categorical description.
Some things are substances at a macro level, but ultimately end up as not being divisible into the same kind of thing.  E.g., sand vs. grains of sand, bacteria vs. an individual bacterium.

definition.value: An event characterized by a defined piece of work that is either scheduled, accomplished, or both.

scopeNote.value: Note that this differs from the ordinary sense of 'task,' which is not an event (e.g., 'A piece of work to be done or undertaken.').

definition.value: An event that can be said to have occurred at some place in space.

example.value: A meeting, a car accident.
Negative examples: Excludes events that have no meaningful location, such as financial events or project milestones.

definition.value: A device that can affect the real world via a message interface
A project is a task (usually a longer duration task) made up of other tasks.
A collection of People. The group may or may not be an Organization.  Many organizations consist of groups of people, but that is not a defining characteristic.
Something which two or more People or Organizations mutually commit to do.
Each pulse from a Sensor is reflected in a message, as well as each instruction to an Actuator
A unit to measure linear distance, such as feet or kilometers.

A measure of the wavelength-weighted power emitted by a light source in a particular direction per unit solid angle.  This is based on the luminosity function, a standardized model of the sensitivity of the human eye.
A measure that was neither measured nor estimated but set by fiat. For instance, a goal. There is no Measurement associated with a ReferenceValue.
A device that can detect something and report it. Light sensors, temperature sensors,
Something that occurs over some period of time, often characterized as an activity being carried out by some person, organization, or software application.
A set of codes the postal authorities can use to deliver physical mail.

example.value: A street address, a PO Box, an FPO code, or the route codes.

definition.value: The algorithm for getting from Greenwich Mean Time to local time, which includes the time zone offset and rules about daylight savings time.
The time zone containing the Royal Observatory in Greenwich, England, which is located on the prime meridian.
A unit representing the amount of matter in a particle or object.  The SI unit of mass is the kilogram.
Amount of chemical material.  Measured in Avogadro units (moles) of 6.02 x 10^23 molecules.
A product unit both of whose factors are coherent units. The conversion factor is 1.

example.value: Square meter, an area unit.

note.value: While a country government may enter into treaties with other country governments, that does not mean it is 'governed by' the others.

definition.value: A Government Organization which asserts both sovereignty (i.e., it is not governed by some other government organization) and governance over an entity generally recognized as a 'country'.
A commitment to buy or sell a described or identified part or service.
A unit to measure amounts of digital information.
An obligation (possibly unilateral).
Unit of electrical current, which is charge per unit time.  The SI unit is the ampere.  (Note that electrical current is a composed unit.)
Any of many ways of categorizing products, including models, NATO product codes, and the like.
A work, invention or concept, independent of its being expressed in text, audio, video, image, or live performance.  IP can also be tacit knowledge, know-how, or skill. Also includes Brands.

scopeNote.value: For literature this could be called the ?Work?, except that ?work? is a highly overloaded term (expenditure of energy, resource consumption, art).  Often the first expression precedes our recognition of the IP, but subsequent expressions are known to be derivatives of the IP, even if they are expression-to-expression translations (or copies).

example.value: The Old Man and The Sea; the Page Rank algorithm; Coca Cola

definition.value: A recognized, organized set of symbols and grammar.

example.value: Natural languages such as English and Spanish; computer languages such as OWL, Python, and XML.

definition.value: Any combination of descriptions of things offered together.  Could be a kit (several parts offered together), but could also be a product plus a warranty.
A unit of money. Note: this is the only unit whose conversion factors include time (i.e., the conversion rates change on a daily basis).
A ratio where the numerator and denominator are of the same unit of measure.

scopeNote.value: There are various ways to represent percentage: 50/100 could be represented as ?50? or ?0.5?.  gist uses the latter, as it involves fewer conversions for subsequent use.

definition.value: An abstract representation of the connection between two or more nodes in a network.

scopeNote.value: Each NetworkLink is connected to a NetworkNode via the property 'gist:links' or one of its subproperties.

example.value: A network link may be physical, such as pipes, wired or wireless networks, but may also be a link in a non-physical network, such as organizational structures or social networks.

definition.value: Intellectual Property reduced to text, audio etc.  If it contains text (written or spoken), it may be in a language.
A collection of terms approved and managed by some organization or person.
Time, but not on a timeline.

scopeNote.value: Intervals have durations, but are not themselves durations.

example.value: One week (or seven days), but not Jan 1, 2008 to Jan 7, 2008 (which is an interval).

definition.value: A duration equal to 24 hours.

scopeNote.value: This is a gist:Magnutude, not a unit of measure, it means essentially the same thing as the unit, day.

definition.value: A duration equal to one millisecond.

scopeNote.value: This is a gist:Magnutude, not a unit of measure, it means essentially the same thing as the unit, millisecond.

definition.value: A duration equal to one minute.

scopeNote.value: This is a gist:Magnutude, not a unit of measure, it means essentially the same thing as the unit, minute.

definition.value: A specification of some aspect of a contract.
A system is an artifact with component parts where the parts contribute to the goal of the system
A relationship existing for a period of time.

scopeNote.value: A temporal relation must be gist:isConnectedTo a minimum of two objects. For example, a temporal relation representing a period of employment is connected both to the person and to the role/position they held.

example.value: employs-Employment, hasStreetAddress-EstablishedLocation. One important context for reifying a property.

definition.value: An email address is a unique identifier for an email account. It is used to both send and receive email messages over the Internet.
Something permanently attached to the Earth.
Something that is currently, or at some point in time was, alive.

scopeNote.value: Not all life forms have exactly two parents, so the restriction only specifies a minimum of one.

example.value: Negative examples: fictional life forms such as unicorns or Mickey Mouse.
A cat, a mushroom, a tree.

definition.value: An Agreement which can be enforced by law
A description of a product or service to be delivered, given in a sufficient level of detail that a receiver could determine whether delivery constituted discharge of the obligation to deliver.

scopeNote.value: In short, an unambiguous characterization of what it is that a potential buyer is paying for.

definition.value: A documented physical or functional need that a particular design, product, or process must be able to perform.  Alternately, the obligation of a person or organization to behave in a certain way (i.e., drive on the right side of the road).
Standard unit by which we measure things
An intentional, person-made thing, which could be physical or content
A controlled vocabulary arranged as a hierarchy of concepts.
Magnitude of mass.
A defined geographical area (or areas) governed by exactly one country government.
A device that takes messages or signals from a sensor and decides through algorithms whether and which actuator to fire via messages
This is for folksonomy type terms, which can be made up on the fly by users.
A specific intentional endpoint.  One can tell whether it has been achieved, as opposed to an intention, which may not have an evaluation function.

A primitive unit that cannot be decomposed into other units. It can be converted from one measurement system to another.  The base units in gist are the seven primitive units from the System Internationale (SI): (meter, second, kilogram, ampere, kelvin, mole, candela), plus three convenience ones: each. bit and usDollar.
The base unit for measuring digital information.

scopeNote.value: A bit (short for binary digit) is the smallest unit of data in a computer. A bit has a single binary value, either 0 or 1.

definition.value: The base unit for currency.
The base unit for measuring temperature.
The base unit for measuring molar quantities.
The base unit for measuring distance.
The base unit for luminous intensity.
The base unit for count magnitudes.
The base unit for measuring mass.
The base unit for measuring durations.
The base unit for electrical current.
A set of requirements to be satisfied by a material, design, product, or service.
A unit of two-dimensional area, such as square inches or hectares.
An event which has an effect on at least one accumulator.
An address which references a fixed location in the physical world.

scopeNote.value: This excludes addresses not associated with a fixed location, such as a PO box or FPO code.

example.value: The street address of a building, a park, campground, or an empty lot.

definition.value: Any identifiable grouping of instances.  For instance, a jury is a collection of people.

example.value: A jury is a group of people,   a financial ledger is a collection of transaction entries; a route is an (ordered) collection of segments.

definition.value: The degree or intensity of heat present in a substance or object, especially as expressed according to a comparative scale.
A specific instance of content sent from an Organization or Person to at least one other Organization or Person.

example.value: An email message, a phone call, a voice message, or a Web Service message.

definition.value: An amount decremented or incremented by a series of transactions.
A task planned to occur.  When it was scheduled, it would have been in the future, but now might be in the past.

Something used to make instances in its own image.  In manufacturing this would be specialized as a die to make stamped parts, cookie cutters are templates for cookies, and forms are templates for data.

scopeNote.value: Use gist:isBasedOn to link the instantiation of a template back to its Template.

example.value: A form. A filled-in form has the structure of the form with data entered into some or all of the fields.

definition.value: A numeric code a telephonic device uses for contacting another telephonic device.

example.value: Mobile, fax, or landline phone number.

definition.value: A single portion of a GeoRegion which has been divided (i.e., segmented).
A unit to measure passage of time: hours, days, years.
A duration unit that is 24 hours long.
A unit equal to a thousandth of a second.
A unit equal to 60 seconds.
A special type of magnitude, due to the way rounding is handled in math and the temporal aspect of conversion.
An obligation that is not yet firm.  There is some contingent event, the occurrence of which will cause the obligation to become firm.

scopeNote.value: A contingent obligation might have a getter counterparty (as in the case of insurance); but it might not (as in the case of an offer).

definition.value: A very general term for the characteristic of something that is being measured.  E.g., property (height) or a process (cycle time) or a behavior (loyalty).

Each simple unit has a base unit and a conversion factor to the base. The bases are from the System International (SI). The conversion factor is the number which one multiplies a Unit by to get to base, or divides by to get from base.  E.g., the conversionFactor for inch is 0.0254 to get to the base unit (meter).
A measure of distance, which could be distances over the Earth, and could also be height, width, length, depth, girth, etc.

A region that observes a uniform standard time for legal, commercial, and social purposes.  A typical time zone averages 15? of longitude in width and typically observes a clock time one hour earlier than the zone immediately to the east.
Three-dimensional space, or equivalent fluid measurement.
A concept or label used to categorize other instances informally. Things that can be thought of as types are usually Categories.

example.value: Tags used in folksonomies; formal definitions from other systems.

scopeNote.value: Often a 'bucket' can be modeled either as an owl:Class or as a gist:Category. Use the latter if you don't care much about the formal structure of the different types, or if there is a whole hierarchy of types that are going to be managed by a group separate from the ontology developers. The formal structure may be defined elsewhere and linked to, if necessary.

definition.value: The measure of brightness. The SI unit is the candela.
Union of all the geo classes

An organization which exercises political and/or regulatory authority over a political unit, people, geo-region, etc., as well as performing certain functions for this unit or body. Differs from a corporation in that it cannot be owned.

scopeNote.value: Includes administrative, regulatory, and enforcement organizations created or sanctioned by Country or SubCountry Governments.

example.value: The State of Washington Office of Financial Management; the Food and Drug Administration; the Scottish Parliament.

definition.value: An organization whose members are government organizations.

example.value: The United Nations, the European Union

definition.value: A digitized type that computer applications can recognize.
A UnitOfMeasure composed of a numerator unit and a denominator unit.

example.value: Miles per hour.

scopeNote.value: If needed, a conversion factor for a RatioUnit can be (recursively) derived from the conversion factors of the numerator and denominator units.  E.g., the derived conversion factor from km/minute to meters/second is 1000/60 or 16 2/3.

definition.value: The effects to be realized in the real world, such as lifting a garage door, turning off a valve, dropping cadmium rods, etc.
A unit of measure that is the product of two simpler ones.

example.value: Area and Volume are the classic cases.  But other, more exotic cases exist, such as Newtons.

scopeNote.value: A ProductUnit is intended have a value for conversionFactor.

definition.value: A document, program, image, etc.  (Categories are not content until they are written down.)
A kind of controller.
An organization whose members are country governments.

example.value: NATO, the Louisiana Purchase, the Treaty of Versailles

definition.value: A member of an ordered collection serving as a proxy for a real world item, which can appear in different orders in different collections. The ordered member appears in exactly one ordered collection.

scopeNote.value: An ordered member points to the real world item via the providesOrderFor property. Ordering information is represented either as a number in a sequence, or by preceding or following another ordered member.

example.value: A person may rank 12th in the Boston Marathon but 29th in the New York City Marathon.

definition.value: A future commitment from one organization or person to another. Contracts are sets of obligations to do or forbear, or to indemnify or warrant.

scopeNote.value: Obligations will often be governed by some Agreement or Offer.

definition.value: An amount of data, such as 6 petabytes, or 640KB.
This is a number whose unit of measure is a ratio.

example.value: Speed.  The ratio magnitude is 60, the unit of measure might be MilesPerHour.

scopeNote.value: A RatioMagnitude just has one decimal value.

definition.value: Superclass for all types of metadata, including owl concepts (such as class) and relational (tables, elements) and tool related (queries, R2RML maps etc etc)
A man-made structure for dwelling or working.
A government of a governed geo-region other than a country, which is under the direct or indirect control of a country government.

scopeNote.value: Across the world, there are a variety of types of subsections of a country and the governments thereof (as well as different terms, like 'province' and 'state', which refer to essentially the same type of thing). We should not automatically assume 'state', 'county', and 'city'.  It is more future-proof just to mint the instances using the generic SubCountryGovernment and, where greater specificity is needed, define categories or subclasses.
Note that the predicate 'governs' is used both for the relationship a government has to a governed geo-region, and for the relationship one government has to the governments of its sub-regions.
This class applies only to organizations governing geo-regions. Regulatory and bureaucratic organizations are members of the more generic GovernmentOrganization class.

definition.value: A way of categorizing events.  E.g., differentiating drilling versus cutting.
Unit of measurement for expressing temperature.  Per SI, the base of temperature is in Kelvin, to allow for all units to be expressed relative to a real (in this case absolute) zero.
A ratio unit whose conversion factor is 1.

example.value: Newton, a force unit also expressed as kg-m/s^2

definition.value: A three-dimensional space on or near the surface of the Earth, such as an oil reservoir, the body of a lake, or an airspace.
You could, at least in principle, put an RFID tag on members of this class. Physical things are made of something.  E.g., statues are made of bronze.

example.value: A computer, a book.
Negative example: A discontinuous thing like a manufacturing line cannot reasonably have an RFID attached to it, even though its parts are not the same kind of thing as the whole.

scopeNote.value: In practice, this always means that the parts are not the same kind of thing as the whole.

definition.value: Base class for units which can be converted.  The primitive units can be converted from one measurement system to another; the complex units (ratio or product) have to decompose to their primitives.

scopeNote.value: The precision should be in the same type of unit as the magnitude.

Magnitudes of the same dimensional type (i.e., duration or electric current) can be compared with a greater-than or less-than operator, but can still differ in their relationToTheWorld type.  (I.e., you can compare actuals to estimates or references, so long as the dimension is the same.)

definition.value: Goal, desire, aspiration. This is the "teleologic" aspect of the system that indicates things are done with a purpose.

An individual point on the Earth's surface, identified by latitude, longitude and altitude. If altitude is missing, it is assumed to be at the Earth's surface.  However, altitude is measured from sea level.  these points are to the WGS-84 coordinate system using the GPS decimal lat/long

scopeNote.value: Assume coordinate system used by Google (WGS 84 Web Mercator).

definition.value: Tangible property other than land or buildings.  Any kind of equipment, could be machine, router, car etc.
Categories of equipment
The real-world media type for content.

example.value: Audio, still image, video, textual, physical (e.g., a statue), or performance (i.e. a play).  Or it could be oil or pastel for a painting.

definition.value: A defined geographic area or areas governed by at least one government organization.

scopeNote.value: Geographic regions do not need not be physically contiguous in order to constitute a governed geo-region; e.g., Alaska and Hawaii.

definition.value: A physicality on which a work could be implemented or exposed. E.g., paper, clay, or a computer monitor.
A node in a network.

example.value: A person is a node in a social network; a valve is a node in a network of pipes.

definition.value: A unit that is expressed in units that have no conversions.  It may be a simple unit.  It may also be a product or ratio unit that bottoms out in simple units.

example.value: The standard unit for acceleration is meters per square second (feet per square second  requires a conversion)
A simple unit: kilogram

scopeNote.value: In principle, the CoherentUnit for a ProductUnit or RatioUnit can be inferred by recursively decomposing the products and ratios into their respective CoherentUnits, bottoming out in SimpleUnits
Coherent unit is the physics term for this, informally you might think of it as the standard unit for a given dimension.

definition.value: A measure that involves countable amounts (?eaches? as well as cases, etc.). Can be decimal.

scopeNote.value: Count is not disjoint with all the other magnitudes, as there are some magnitudes that could conceivably be counted.

definition.value: A measurement of two-dimensional space.
An event which, at the time it is created, is to occur in the future.
Content which is in a particular format. (E.g., HTML, PDF, JPG.)

A component is an artifact that contributes to a system.  Could be a simple mechanical component, such as the float contributing to the toilet tank maintaining a constant level, or much more complex as in the internet of things.
An outline of a task of a particular type, that will, when instantiated, generate an actual (unscheduled) task.
The actual date and time that something started, with precision of one minute.

scopeNote.value: Used for things like meetings and time card entries, where the hour and minute are important. Recommended usage is to zero out the seconds and microseconds to avoid spurious precision.

definition.value: The standard symbol for the unit in HTML format for  pretty printing, may use special characters.  E.g. to show square meter as  m? rather than m^2, the value of this property would be "m²" This is for when Unicode not supported and the display will be HTML format.
The date some living thing was or will be born, with precision of one day.

scopeNote.value: This is a subproperty of gist:startDateTime rather than gist:actualStartDate because some living things have yet to be born. This property refers to a calendar date and is assumed to precision of one day (time zone offset is allowed). It is recommended to zero out the hours through microseconds to avoid spurious precision. Implementations requiring a birthdate to the minute can define a subproperty.

definition.value: The thing the identifier refers to.
The subject category is inclusive of, or broader than, the object category. Everything categorized by the subcategory can be inferred to be categorized by the supercategory.

scopeNote.value: This is essentially the same as skos:narrowerTransitive, using gist:Category instead of skos:Concept.

definition.value: Relates a parent category to a child category in an informal (e.g., faceted) hierarchy.

example.value: Refrigerator handles are not refrigerators, but it may be useful to represent their relationship hierarchically for a faceted UI filter.

definition.value: Links a member of an ordered collection to the real-world item it represents in that collection.
A non-owning, non-causal, non-subordinate (i.e., peer-to-peer) relationship.
Origin
The standard symbol for the unit preferred for pretty printing, may use special characters.  E.g. square meter would be  m? rather than m^2.
The standard symbol for the unit NOT using any special characters.  E.g. square meter would be m^2 rather than m?.
Connection between an ID and the thing that minted the ID.  It may be a person or organization, or could be an algorithm (next available or random number generator)

Links a Magnitude to the degree of accuracy of the numeric value.   This allows for fuzzy numbers.  All magnitudes have a precision.  Usually we don't record them.  When we do this, it will be a value whose extent covers 2 standard deviations around the stated magnitude

example.value: Temperature precise to tenth of a degree C; length precise to the nearest centimeter.

definition.value: The intention (say a law) is intended to prevent this kind of behavior (say jay-walking)
The actual date and time that something ended, with no implied precision.

scopeNote.value: This is an abstraction over the various precisions of actual start time, and is not expected to be asserted directly. Values with different precisions can be compared since they all have the same format.

definition.value: To have a comparable numeric value. Each magnitude has a unit.
The active party, the one with the obligation or the one initiating the transfer
The actual date and time that something ended, with no implied precision.

scopeNote.value: This is an abstraction over the various precisions of actual end time, and is not expected to be asserted directly. Values with different precisions can be compared since they all have the same format.

definition.value: The people or organizations participating in an event, agreement or obligation

example.value: For loan agreements, one might create hasLender and hasBorrower as subproperties of hasParty.

definition.value: The transitive version of gist:isDirectPartOf
Relates something (e.g. an agreement) to things that play a role, or take part or are otherwise involved in some way.

example.value: An event of transferring money has a participating account that receives the money.

scopeNote.value: The thing with participants will often be an agreement, event or obligation.
This is intended as an abstract property. Only its subproperties will be directly used.

definition.value: Possessing and controlling.  Ultimate form of ownership is the right to destroy.  Long list of potential Range classes
Relates a NetworkLink to a NetworkNode that it connects to another node. Used when the connections are undirected, or the direction is not known.
Degrees from GM
The entity that formally acknowledges the existence of, as the State recognizes the existence of a particular company
Used for folksonomy style categories (non controlled vocabulary)
Used for taxos that must have single parents
The conversion factor used to convert a unit to its standard (i.e., coherent) unit (which could be a base unit.)

scopeNote.value: Sometimes this property must be used in conjunction with conversionOffset. Kelvin =  (Degrees F - conversionOffset) * conversionFactor. Or K = (F-(-469.67)) * (5/9).

example.value: An area expressed as 7 square kilometers is multiplied by a conversion factor of one million which results in 7 million square meters.
A value expressed in inches is multiplied by a conversion factor of 0.0254 to express the value in the base unit, meter.

definition.value: The transitive version of gist:hasDirectPart
The actual date and time that something ended, with precision of one minute.

scopeNote.value: Used for things like meetings and time card entries, where the hour and minute are important. Recommended usage is to zero out the seconds and microseconds to avoid spurious precision.

definition.value: Relates a ProductUnit such as square mile to the second of two units multiplied together (e.g. mile).
The parts of a system contribute to the goal/ function of the whole system
The subject category is included by, or narrower than, the object category. Everything categorized by the subcategory can be inferred to be categorized by the supercategory.

scopeNote.value: This is essentially the same as skos:broaderTransitive, using gist:Category instead of skos:Concept.

definition.value: The actual time that something started, expressed as a system time used for timestamps.

scopeNote.value: A system time will be as precise as the system can supply, typically at least milliseconds, sometimes microseconds. The convention for timestamps, such as recording a transaction, is to specify just the end point; the start time is rarely needed. This property is defined for the cases when you do need to capture the runtime of a system process, and is then used in conjunction with gist:actualEndMicrosecond.

definition.value: Degrees above or below equator
The date that something is or was planned to end, with precision of one day.

scopeNote.value: Used for anything with a planned end date, such as when a lease will expire, when an offer is no longer available, etc. Typically a planned date is in the future when first captured, but when tasks run late, we leave the plan where it was and compare it to the actual. Recommended usage is to zero out the hours through microseconds to avoid spurious precision.

definition.value: This is like a URI: a thing can have more than one ID, but each of the IDs must refer to a unique thing.
Recognizes
The actual time that something ended, expressed as a system time used for timestamps.

scopeNote.value: A system time will be as precise as the system can supply, typically at least milliseconds, sometimes microseconds. The convention for timestamps, such as recording a transaction, is to specify just the end point; the start time is rarely needed.

definition.value: A generic ordering relation indicating that the subject comes immediately before the object.

scopeNote.value: It is safest to use this property only when the directness has a semantic correspondence with the world. Only break a direct link by inserting an intermediate item when that change corresponds to a change in the world.

definition.value: A generic ordering relation indicating that the subject has the same order as or comes before the object. The 'greater than or equal to' symbol is often used for this relation.
Relates a RatioUnit such as meters/second to the denominator Unit (e.g. second).
Relates something to a substance that it is made up of.

example.value: The vase is made up of clay. Water is made up of hydrogen and oxygen.

definition.value: All the upper tasks this task belongs to
Relates a NetworkLink to its origin NetworkNode. Unlike the superproperty, this represents a directed connection.
Relates a subject category to a unique parent category in an informal (e.g., faceted) hierarchy.

Date that something was posted, not necessarily the date it occurred. Must be after the date of occurrence, but could be before or after the planned date. (Unusual, but I could record today that I expected to be paid last week.)

definition.value: The date and time at which something did or will occur, with variants for precision, start and end, and actual vs. planned.

scopeNote.value:
This is the top level property for asserting time, and is not expected to be asserted directly.

The subproperties allow the ontologist to do three things:
1) Distinguish start and end times.
2) Indicate whether a time is planned or actual. This is useful for everything from project management to calendar appointments and the like. It is also useful for date effectivities; i.e., something valid up to a planned date).
3) Distinguish varying levels of precision; sort of a simple version of the Allen functions.  

All datetimes are of the same format: '2021-06-01T08:03:27.12324-6:00'^^xsd:dateTime. This is compatible with and a subset of ISO 8601.

Time zone offset, such as -6:00 (of which there are a few dozen) is recognized in the date itself, as shown. The actual time zone standard (of which there are 131) may optionally be attached to the event or other object itself; see property gist:usesTimeZoneStandard.

There will be many historical dates that do not have a time zone offset (e.g., Lincoln's birthday, as well as about 75% of all legacy systems), and in that case the offset can be omitted. 

The conventions for precision that are repeated in each property name are as follows:
	- *DateTime is an abstraction over the various precisions of its subproperties.
	- *Date refers to a calendar date (e.g., birthdays and invoice dates) and is assumed to have precision of one day. Time zone offset is allowed.
	- *Minute refers to clock time; e.g., a meeting will start at 9:15 with a timezone offset. Precision is assumed to have precision of one minute.
	- *Microsecond refers to system time, and it will be as precise as the system can supply; typically at least milliseconds, sometime microseconds.
